node.text: This #MemorialDay, we pause to honor and remember the sacrifice of Colonel Roy A. Knight and the homecoming that we, and Roy's son, retired Southwest Captain Bryan Knight, will never forget. Captain Knight said goodbye to his father at Dallas Love Field Airport when he was deployed to serve in the Vietnam War in 1966. In 2019, more than 50 years after Roy went missing in action, Captain Knight flew his father home for the final time. Read more about how we honor our military heroes: http://swa.is/HonoringOurHeroes

node.text:
Ever attend a wedding at 35,000 ft?

York, a Southwest Pilot, met Sabrina, a fellow aviation-lover, in person for the first time at a Southwest ticket counter at LAS. Sabrina, a nurse from Seattle, would join York's trips on her days off, allowing the two to travel together from city to city as their relationship developed.

Finally, York proposed to Sabrina during a private flight over the mountains in Utah. It was only fitting, then, that the couple tie the knot in a special ceremony aboard a Southwest flight from Las Vegas, where they first met, to Salt Lake City. Congrats, York and Sabrina! Wishing you both a lifetime of peace and happiness from the Love Airline. #SouthwestHeart

node.text:
Luke used to have a fear of flying. Eventually, his parents convinced him to fly on Southwest, and suffice it to say, it was love at first flight. Luke developed a strong passion for aviation, and even built a Southwest-themed flight simulator in his house. 

Now, Luke has dreams of one day becoming a Southwest Pilot. When we heard of his story, we invited him to our station in Nashville to give him the VIP tour. Several Employees in Nashville came together to roll out the red carpet. See you on the flight deck, Luke! #SouthwestHeart
